<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike their red counterparts, most rosé wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment, but understanding their aging potential is crucial for the discerning wine enthusiast.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>

<p><strong>Everyday rosés</strong> (Provence-style, simple saignée wines) reach peak enjoyment within 1-2 years of vintage. These wines rely on fresh fruit aromatics and crisp acidity that diminish with extended cellaring.</p>

<p><strong>Premium rosés</strong> from renowned producers like Domaine Tempier Bandol or Château d'Esclans Garrus can evolve beautifully for 3-5 years. Their higher tannin content from extended skin contact and superior terroir provide structural backbone for graceful aging.</p>

<p><strong>Champagne rosé and serious sparkling rosés</strong> offer the longest cellaring potential, developing complex tertiary aromas of brioche and dried fruits over 5-8 years.</p>

<h3>Evolution in the Bottle</h3>

<p>During proper aging, rosé undergoes fascinating transformations. Primary fruit flavors of strawberry and watermelon evolve into more complex notes of dried herbs, orange peel, and subtle spice. The wine's color typically deepens from pale salmon to amber-tinged copper as anthocyanins oxidize slowly.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store rosé at consistent <strong>55°F (13°C)</strong> with 70% humidity. Unlike reds, rosé is particularly sensitive to light exposure—UV rays can cause premature color degradation and off-flavors. Keep bottles horizontal in complete darkness.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Development</h3>

<p>Well-aged rosé develops integrated flavors where acidity mellows while maintaining freshness. Warning signs of spoilage include brown discoloration, oxidized aromas resembling sherry or vinegar, and complete loss of fruit character. When in doubt, most rosés are best enjoyed within their first two years when their vibrant character truly shines.</p>

