  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all rosé is sweet – many premium rosés are bone dry with complex minerality. Another error is buying rosé that's over two years old, as most are meant to be consumed young for optimal freshness. Many people also overlook the production method, not realizing that saignée rosés (made as a byproduct of red wine) often have more intensity than rosés made specifically from direct pressing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is rosé wine a good choice for beginners compared to red or white wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé is exceptionally beginner-friendly because it bridges the gap between white and red wines, offering fruit-forward flavors without the tannin structure that can be challenging for new wine drinkers. The refreshing acidity and food-friendly nature make rosé forgiving with various cuisines, while the visual appeal of the pink color adds to its approachability. Quality entry-level options from regions like Côtes de Provence or Loire Valley provide excellent introduction to wine appreciation without overwhelming complexity.</p>
